# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ee-times
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The website has come under scrutiny from many governments starting in the late 2010s, including bans in China and Russia and in 2025 U.S.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed a domain registrar to identify the owner of archive.today's domain name.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] archive.today was founded in 2012 as a web archive.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] It allegedly registered its trademark in the Czech Republic in 2013.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The site originally branded itself as archive.today, but changed the primary mirror to archive.is in May 2015.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] It began to deprecate the archive.is domain in favor of other mirrors in January 2019.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] According to the archive.today blog, the website had saved about 500 million pages by 2021, 700 terabytes in total size.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In July 2013, archive.today began supporting the API of the Memento Project at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Due to budget constraints at LANL, the Memento Project was disestablished in September 2025.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Archive.today was one of the last major active users of the Memento protocol following the project's downsizing.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The closure of the Memento infrastructure at LANL in September 2025 came amid a broader period of increased scrutiny for the service.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Individual profile pages on 200.zona.media link to snapshots of social media posts by relatives, obituaries in local media, and other open-source evidence used to verify each death.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In early 2023, a team of researchers at the University of Amsterdam identified archive.today as the most-used open-access archiving service among fact-checking organisations, based on the European Digital Media Observatory's dataset on the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] On 5 August 2023, Jani Patokallio published on his blog *Gyrovague* an investigation regarding archive.today's funding sources and the founder's identity.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] On 30 October 2025, the US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed archive.today's domain registrar, Tucows.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The subpoena stated its purpose was to identify the owner(s) of the archive.today domain name, and that it was part of a criminal investigation conducted by the FBI, the nature of which was not disclosed.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] News coverage of the subpoena mentioned Patokallio's report, where Patokallio has said there were "several indications" the founder was based in Russia.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In November 2025, the DNS provider AdGuard DNS reported that a French organization *Web Abuse Association Defense* (WAAD) had pressured it to block archive.today and its mirror domains.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] WAAD alleged that archive.today had refused to remove child sexual abuse material since 2023.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] When AdGuard contacted archive.today, the archive removed the material, stating that it had never received prior complaints about those URLs.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] AdGuard found WAAD suspicious as a recently registered association with minimal public presence, noting evidence of possible impersonation of a real French lawyer in similar WAAD complaints sent to other companies.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] AdGuard announced it would file a criminal complaint with French police.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] On 14 January 2026, it emerged that archive.today had silently modified its CAPTCHA page to send repeated requests to *Gyrovague*, thereby causing visitors to unwittingly contribute to a DDOS attack against the blog.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The archive.today blog simultaneously posted several public criticisms of Patokallio.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Emails released by Patokallio show archive.today requesting the temporary removal of his report and later threatening him with AI pornography.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The community's decision was made despite concerns over maintaining content verifiability—partly undermined by the discovery of the alterations— while removing and replacing the second-largest archiving service used across the Wikimedia Foundation's projects.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The Wikimedia Foundation had stated its readiness to take action regardless of the community verdict.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Patokallio expressed his satisfaction with the outcome.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] This was not the first time Wikipedia had restricted links to archive.today.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In 2013, the community blacklisted archive.is, citing concerns about botnets, linkspamming, and the opaque manner in which the site was operated.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The decision was overturned in 2016 following a new request for comment, and archive.today was removed from the spam blacklist.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] At the time of the 2026 ban, the site was the second-largest archiving service used across all Wikimedia Foundation projects, with over 695,000 links spread across approximately 400,000 pages.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] archive.today can capture individual pages in response to explicit user requests.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Since its beginning, it has supported crawling pages with URLs containing the now-deprecated hash-bang fragment (#!).
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The website records only text and images, excluding XML, RTF, spreadsheet (xls or ods) and other non-static content.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] However, videos for certain sites, like Twitter, are saved.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] It keeps track of the history of snapshots saved, requesting confirmation before adding a new snapshot of an already saved page.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Once a web page is archived, it cannot be deleted directly by any Internet user.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Pages are captured at a browser width of 1,024 pixels.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] CSS is converted to inline CSS, removing responsive web design and selectors such as `:hover` and `:active`.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Content generated using JavaScript during the crawling process appears in a frozen state.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] HTML class names are preserved inside the `old-class` attribute.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] When text is selected, a JavaScript applet generates a URL fragment seen in the browser's address bar that automatically highlights that portion of the text when visited again.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Web pages can be duplicated from archive.today to web.archive.org as second-level backup, but archive.today does not save its snapshots in WARC format.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The reverse—from web.archive.org to archive.today—is also possible, but the copy usually takes more time than a direct capture.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] While saving a page, a list of URLs for individual page elements and their content sizes, HTTP statuses and MIME types is shown.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] This list can only be viewed during the crawling process.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Removing advertisements, popups or expanding links from archived pages is possible by asking the owner to do it on his blog.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] According to the site's FAQ, archive.today's storage layer runs on Apache Hadoop and Apache Accumulo, with all data stored on the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Textual content is replicated three times across servers in two data centers, both located in Europe, with at least one hosted by the French provider OVH; images are replicated twice.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The site does not store snapshots in WARC format.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The scraping component has used a modified version of the Chromium browser since November 2019, replacing the previous PhantomJS-based engine.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The research toolbar enables advanced keywords operators, using `*` as the wildcard character.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Paired quotation marks address the search to an exact sequence of keywords present in the title or in the body of the webpage, whereas the *insite* operator restricts it to a specific Internet domain.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] While saving a dynamic list, archive.today search box shows only a result that links the previous and the following section of the list (e.g.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The other web pages saved are filtered, and sometimes may be found by one of their occurrences.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The search feature is backed by Google CustomSearch.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] If it delivers no results, archive.today attempts to utilize Yandex Search.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] archive.today is frequently used to bypass paywalls on news websites, similarly to the defunct service 12ft.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The practice of sharing archive.today links to circumvent paywalls has sparked legal and ethical debate in Europe.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In the Netherlands, journalist Peter Aanzee publicly challenged a physician who shared an archive.ph link to one of his paywalled articles in *De Volkskrant*, arguing that distributing archived copies constituted copyright infringement.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Commentators have contrasted archive.today with the Internet Archive's Wayback Machine.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The same paywalled *Volkskrant* article shared via archive.ph was also found archived in the Wayback Machine, demonstrating that both services can be used to circumvent paywalls.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Like the Wayback Machine, archive.today does not advertise paywall circumvention among its stated features; the ability to bypass paywalls is a byproduct of its core function of archiving web pages as they appear to visitors.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] A 2025 investigation by journalist Henk van Ess found that AI chatbots—including ChatGPT, Perplexity AI, Grok, and Claude—exploit web archives to bypass paywalls during live web searches.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In one documented case, ChatGPT retrieved a full article from *The Economist* via archive.today and then generated a five-point economic analysis in the publication's characteristic style and terminology.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Van Ess identified six distinct methods of paywall circumvention by AI systems, of which "archive exploitation"—finding archived copies on services such as archive.today and the Internet Archive—was the most direct.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Unlike documented concerns about AI training unpaywalled content, this behaviour involves real-time retrieval through archived copies during individual queries, effectively extending paywall circumvention beyond human users to automated agents.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The researchers documented that archive.is URLs were extensively shared on "fringe" communities such as 4chan's /pol/ board and the Reddit subreddit r/The_Donald, both to preserve potentially contentious content and to deny ad revenue to news outlets perceived as ideologically opposed.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Moderation bots on r/The_Donald automatically blocked direct links to certain news sites—for example, 46% of links to the *New York Daily News* were censored—and prompted users to post archive.is URLs instead.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] The authors estimated that *The Washington Post* lost approximately US$70,000 per year in ad revenue due to the practice of sharing archived copies rather than direct links on Reddit alone.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] On Reddit, bots were responsible for posting 44% of archive.is links and 85% of Wayback Machine links across the studied subreddits, driven by moderators aiming to mitigate link rot.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] A 2023 study by researchers at the University of Amsterdam, as part of the vera.ai project, examined 1,991 fact-checking articles from the European Digital Media Observatory's "War in Ukraine" dataset.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Of 41,758 extracted links, 6,002 were archived pages. archive.today was the most-used link archiving service, at 44.1%, ahead of the Internet Archive/Wayback Machine (29.2%) and Perma.cc (26.6%).
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Fact-checkers primarily used these services to preserve ephemeral and platform-restricted content, such as Facebook posts that are difficult to capture due to anti-bot measures.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In March 2019, the site was blocked for six months by several internet providers in Australia and New Zealand in the aftermath of the Christchurch mosque shootings in an attempt to limit distribution of the footage of the attack.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] According to GreatFire.org, archive.today has been blocked in mainland China since March 2016, archive.li since September 2017, archive.fo since July 2018, as well as archive.ph since December 2019.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] On 21 July 2015, the archive.today blocked access to the service from all Finnish IP addresses, stating on Twitter that they did this in order to avoid escalating a dispute they allegedly had with the Finnish government.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] Since the conflict with the Finnish blogger in early 2026, the website displays an unpassable captcha to visitors from Finland.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] In 2016, the Russian communications agency Roskomnadzor began blocking access to archive.is from Russia.
[src:ee-times/archive-today] On 23 March 2026, archive.today and several mirror domains were blocked by Russian authorities.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Arrow Electronics was founded in 1935 when a retail store named Arrow Radio opened on Cortlandt Street in the heart of lower Manhattan's "Radio Row", the birthplace of electronics distribution.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Arrow Radio, established by Maurice ("Murray") Goldberg, sold used radios and radio parts to retail customers.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Other industry pioneers with businesses nearby were Charles Avnet and Seymour Schweber.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] By the 1940s, Arrow was selling new radios—manufactured by RCA, GE, and Philco—and other home entertainment products, as well as surplus radio parts that were retailed over-the-counter in a parts department at the back of the store.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Soon the firm started seeking franchises to sell new parts; the first manufacturers to franchise Arrow were RCA and Cornell Dubilier.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] The business was incorporated as Arrow Electronics, Inc., in 1946.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In the early 1950s, with additional franchises and a small field sales organization, Arrow began selling electronic parts to industrial customers.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] A second storefront/sales office was opened in Mineola, Long Island, in 1956.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] By 1961, when the company completed its initial public offering and listed its shares on the American Stock Exchange, total sales amounted to $4 million, over half of which came from the industrial sales division, with the remainder from the traditional retail business.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] During the 1960s, Arrow moved its headquarters to Farmingdale, New York (Long Island), and opened additional branches in Norwalk, Connecticut, and Totowa, New Jersey.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] The company relocated its headquarters office to Centennial, Colorado, in 2011.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In 1968, Glenn, Green & Waddell, a partnership formed by three recent graduates of the Harvard Business School, B.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Waddell, led a private investor group that acquired the controlling interest in Arrow.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] The investors saw an opportunity to consolidate the fragmented electronics industry.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] During the 1970s decade, by winning key semiconductor franchises (led by Texas Instruments in 1970) and opening sales offices in over 20 U.S. cities, Arrow grew its electronics distribution business at an average annual rate of 34 percent.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] By the end of the decade, the company's electronics distribution sales had climbed to $177 million, making Arrow the country's second largest electronics distributor.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] The company took on high levels of debt through frequent public bond offerings, to fund its growth strategy.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Additional growth capital was provided through the 1969 acquisition of Schuylkill Metals Corporation, a lead recycling company.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In the 1970s, Arrow discontinued its retail operations and inaugurated the electronics distribution's first integrated online, real-time computer system to provide up-to-the-minute inventory positions and facilitate remote order entry.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In 1979, Arrow was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] That same year, it acquired Cramer Electronics (historically the U.S.'s second-largest distributor), the company's first major industry acquisition, which provided access to many markets in the western United States.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] On December 4, 1980, the Stouffer's Inn Fire killed 13 members of Arrow's senior management, including Glenn and Green.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Waddell assumed leadership and, in 1982, recruited Stephen P.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Kaufman, formerly a partner of McKinsey & Company, to join Arrow as president of the company's electronics distribution division.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Kaufman succeeded Waddell as CEO in 1986 and as chairman in 1994.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In 1988, Arrow adopted a growth strategy by acquiring Kierulff Electronics.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] According to Forbes, the company closed down all four Kierulff Electronics warehouses and within a year it experienced "miraculous" growth that went from a bottom line of $16 million loss in 1987 to operating profits of $10 million.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] During his nearly two decades with Arrow, Kaufman led the company's consolidation of the U.S. electronics distribution industry as well as the company's expansion into Europe and the Asia Pacific region.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Under Kaufman's leadership, Arrow completed over 50 acquisitions of electronics distributors, including such prominent names as Ducommun (Kierulff), Lex (Schweber), Zeus, Anthem, Bell, and Wyle (all in the U.S.), Spoerle (Germany), Silverstar (Italy), and CAL (Hong Kong and China).
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Kaufman also led the company into the national distribution of commercial computer products, initially through its acquisition of Gates/FA Distributing.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Arrow entered the 21st century with global electronic component sales of $9 billion and $3 billion of sales in its computer products business.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In 1998, Arrow Electronics established a 50/50 joint venture with Marubun Corporation of Japan called **Marubun/Arrow** in order to augment and support each other's operations in Asia and North America.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Kaufman stepped down as CEO in 2000, retired as chairman in 2002, and was succeeded by Daniel W.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Mitchell, former president of the global services division of Solectron Corporation, joined Arrow as chief executive officer and, in 2006, became chairman.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] During Mitchell's six years at Arrow, sales climbed to $17 billion as the company increased shareholder returns, improved operating efficiencies, and completed 17 acquisitions.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Long succeeded Mitchell as CEO, and in 2010 took over as chairman.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] A long-time Arrow executive, Long joined the company in 1991 through the merger with Schweber Electronics and served in various senior management positions before becoming CEO.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] During Long's tenure, Arrow completed over 40 strategic acquisitions that further expanded its global components and computer systems businesses.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In 2015, Arrow acquired United Technical Publishing from Hearst, adding properties such as *Electronic Products* and Schematics.com.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In June 2016, UBM reached agreement to divest its electronics media portfolio to an affiliate of Arrow Electronics Inc. for a cash consideration of $23.5 million.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] The portfolio comprises the U.S. and Asian versions of EE Times, EDN, ESM, Embedded, EBN, TechOnline and Datasheets.com.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Kerins succeeded Long as president and CEO.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Having joined Arrow in 2007 as vice president of North America storage and networking, Kerins went on to serve as president of the company’s North America enterprise computing solutions business before being named global president of the business in 2014 and then chief operating officer in 2020.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Kerins separated from the company in September 2025.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Arrow is ranked at number 148 on the Fortune 500 list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] The company has also been recognized for 26 years overall on Fortune's “World’s Most Admired Companies” list.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Since 2012, Arrow has been sponsoring FIRST Robotics Competition, an international high school robotics competition.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In 2019, after being a minor sponsor of the team, Arrow became the title sponsor of Schmidt Peterson Motorsport (SPM) IndyCar team to become Arrow Schmidt Peterson Motorsport.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] In the same year, Arrow signed a sponsorship deal with McLaren Racing.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] McLaren would later announce that they will be entering the IndyCar Series with SPM as a joint entry for the 2020 season as Arrow McLaren SP.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] Arrow and McLaren signed a sponsorship extension in 2021 that saw Arrow continue as a sponsor for the McLaren F1 Team and as title sponsor for the IndyCar team, which was rebranded as Arrow McLaren IndyCar Team with the 2023 season.
[src:ee-times/arrow-electronics] The title sponsorship deal will end after the 2028 season.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The City of Centennial was incorporated on February 7, 2001, from portions of unincorporated Arapahoe County, including the former Castlewood and Southglenn census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The citizens of the area had voted to incorporate on September 12, 2000, choosing Centennial as the official name during the vote.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The name reflects Colorado's admission to the Union as the 38th state in 1876, the centennial year of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The state of Colorado is nicknamed the "Centennial State".
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Incorporation was approved by 77% of the voters, and the population of the area at over 100,000 made it the largest incorporation in U.S. history as of its creation.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The city was incorporated in large part to prevent further annexations of unincorporated areas by the city of Greenwood Village in an attempt to improve its tax base.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The taxes generated from businesses in unincorporated portions of Arapahoe County funded the majority of the county's services, including road work.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] A number of court cases eventually established the right of incorporation to take precedence over the right of annexation.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The city was incorporated on a promise to keep city taxes at 1%.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] (One of the campaigns against incorporation appealed to voters to maintain the 3.8% sales tax of the unincorporated county.) According to the Centennial website, the current sales tax rate is two-and-a-half times the promised rate, at 2.5%.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] In 2008, Centennial voters approved a referendum by approximately a 2-to-1 margin making Centennial a home rule city.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Centennial Airport, formerly the Arapahoe County Airport, lies adjacent to Centennial, but is located in unincorporated Arapahoe County.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The airport is not named after the city, as it predates the city by over 30 years.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Centennial is roughly divided in half by Interstate 25, with most of its business and entertainment centers lying west of the highway.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The city's boundaries are highly irregular and evocative of a gerrymander, particularly the overwhelmingly residential eastern portions of the city, which appear with Foxfield, portions of Aurora, and unincorporated areas as a distorted checkerboard on the city's map.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Centennial has many hills, gullies and ravines, and its open spaces are usually accompanied by recreational trails and parks, including Dry Creek Dam, DeKoevend Park, the High Line Canal Trail, Willow Creek Trail, as well as Big Dry Creek and Little Dry Creek Trails.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Centennial hosts most native wildlife and is a good reflection of Colorado's front range ecosystem.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Centennial has seen a boost in coyote populations in recent years, leading to resident education on how to deter coyotes from eating family pets.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] At the 2020 United States census, the city had a total area of 19,115 acres (77.355 km2) including 94 acres (0.379 km2) of water.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The city is approximately composed of 87.4% White, 4.8% Hispanic or Latino, 3.6% Asian, 2.4% African American, 0.4% Native American, and 0.3% from other races.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The median age is 37.2 years, in comparison to the 35.3-year national average.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] For every 100 females, there are 98 males.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] National CineMedia, Emergenetics International and United Launch Alliance are among the companies based in Centennial.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Most of Centennial is within the territory of the Cherry Creek Public Schools while the western portion of the city in the territory of Littleton Public Schools.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Centennial is also served by a few private schools.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The city is governed under the council–manager form of government which limits the power of the city to levy and collect taxes.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The Mayor and Council Members are all part-time officials who hold other full-time jobs.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] As of 2026, the mayor is Christine Sweetland and the city manager is Matt Sturgeon.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Dove Valley, an unincorporated area bordering Centennial, is home to the training facilities and team headquarters for the Denver Broncos, a National Football League franchise that plays in Denver.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The team moved their headquarters to Dove Valley in 1990 and built their training facilities there in 2003.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The Pat Bowlen Fieldhouse was constructed on the campus in 2014 and houses 115,000 square feet (10,700 m2) of training space and offices.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] A major expansion of the team's facilities was announced in 2023 and is planned to be completed in 2023.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] Denver Summit FC in the National Women's Soccer League plans to build their training center in Centennial in a partnership with the city government and the Cherry Creek School District.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The center will include eight fields on 43 acres (17 ha) of land and an indoor training area.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] A temporary 12,000-seat stadium on the grounds is planned to open in 2026 for the team's inaugural season and be used for two seasons while construction of a permanent stadium in Denver is completed.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] The Centennial stadium project is expected to cost up to $25 million with funding from the team and school district.
[src:ee-times/centennial-colorado] After the 2027 season, the stadium's capacity is planned to be reduced to 4,000 seats and continue to be used by the school district.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Headquartered in San Francisco, California, UBM Technology Group was a part of UBM, a global business-to-business (B2B) events organiser which in turn owned by Informa and later absorbed into Informa TechTarget in 2024.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In 1971, Gerard "Gerry" Leeds and his wife, Lilo, founded the company as **CMP Publications Inc.** in Manhasset, New York.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Their sons Michael and Daniel managed the company in 1988, and launched TechWeb in 1994.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] CMP Media acquired McGraw-Hill Information Technology and Communications Group (including *BYTE*) in 1998.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] CMP Media was sold to United News & Media's Miller Freeman in 1999, Miller Freeman subsequently sold CMP UK and France to VNU.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] VNU Business Publications was later acquired by Incisive Media in 2007.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In 2000, the US IT portion of Miller Freeman was merged into CMP.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] CMP Channel (including *CRN* US) was spun off as UBM Channel and later went into management buyout as The Channel Company in 2013.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] The Channel Company later acquired technology division of Incisive Media and gained rights to *CRN* UK in 2022.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] The music portions of CMP and Miller Freeman were spun off as Music Player Network, which managed by CMP Entertainment Media.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] The gaming portion (including Gamasutra and Game Developer Conference) was grouped into CMP GamaNetwork in early 2001.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Black Hat Briefings was acquired in 2005.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In May 2006, CMP Media changed its name to CMP Technology.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In September 2006, NewBay Media acquired CMP Entertainment Media from United Business Media.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] The trade book operations of CMP were sold to Elsevier and Hal Leonard.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In November 2006, Forbes reported that United Business Media had purchased the events assets of MediaLive International Inc.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] This transaction included COMDEX and Interop which later integrated into CMP Technology.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In 2008, United Business Media broke CMP into four divisions inside UBM, notably merged the IT portion of CMP into UBM TechWeb and the electronics portion into UBM Electronics.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] "Today, the name is gone and what's left of the company is part of the British media conglomerate, UBM plc," according to Newsday.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In September 2010, Canon Communications announced that it had agreed to be acquired by United Business Media and the deal was completed in October 2010, at which point the company was renamed UBM Canon.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Electronics part of Canon (including EDN) later merged into UBM Electronics.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In July 2012, UBM TechWeb changed its name to UBM Tech.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] On June 3, 2016, UBM announced that EE Times, along with the rest of the electronics media portfolio (EDN, Embedded.com, TechOnline and Datasheets.com) was being sold to AspenCore Media, a company owned by Arrow Electronics for $23.5 million.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] The acquisition was completed on August 1, 2016.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] In January 2018, Informa announced the acquisition of UBM for £4 billion.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] The transaction was completed in June 2018.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Since the integration of UBM into Informa, UBM Technology Group was absorbed into the technology division of Informa, known as Informa Tech.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Informa Tech later merged its digital business with American business-to-business company TechTarget, became Informa TechTarget in December 2024.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Publications for the builders of technology include Dr.
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] Publications for the buyers of technology include InformationWeek, Network Computing for the corporate IT user; and targeted publications for the financial industry (Wall Street & Technology, Insurance & Technology, and Bank Systems & Technology).
[src:ee-times/cmp-publications-inc] UBM Technology Group (as CMP) co-produces the Web 2.0 Summit along with O'Reilly Media, and formerly the owner of the USPTO Service Mark 'WEB 2.0'.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] Originally launched in 1982 and published by CMP Media of Manhasset, New York, United States, *CRN* was subsequently purchased by London-based United Business Media (UBM) as part of the $920 million acquisition of CMP.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] *Computer Reseller News* later changed its name to the acronym *CRN* and was published by franchise publishers in a number of other countries including Australia, Denmark, Germany, the Netherlands, India, Poland, Russia, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] The headquarters of the magazine is in Westborough, Massachusetts.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] In 2009 *CRN'*s U.S. version was recognized as a leading advertising medium for the IT industry by B2B's Media Power 50 ranking, which called it the "unrivaled leader in covering the channel".
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] In January 2012, the UK version of *CRN* launched the CRN Sales and Marketing Awards.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] These awards recognise and reward the achievements of high-achieving information and communications technology companies.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] In April 2022, The Channel Company acquired *CRN UK*, *Computing*, and Channel Partner Insight from Incisive Media.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] This deal reunited the UK and US edition of *CRN* under common ownership.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] In 2023, The Channel Company relaunched *CRN Germany*.
[src:ee-times/crn-magazine] In March 2025, The Channel Company relaunched *CRN Australia* under an in-house management after previously licensed the brand to nextmedia.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] it was the first issue of *Electrical Design News*, the original name, was published in May 1956 by Rogers Corporation of Englewood, Colorado.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] In January 1961, Cahners Publishing Company, Inc., of Boston, acquired Rogers Publishing Company.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] In February 1966, Cahners sold 40% of its company to International Publishing Company in London In 1970, the Reed Group merged with International Publishing Corporation and changed its name to Reed International Limited moms.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] On April 9, 2013, UBM announced that *EDN*'s print edition would cease publication after the June 2013 issue and that the online *EDN.com* community would continue.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] Michael Dunn led *EDN* through mid-2018.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] Santo succeeded him shortly thereafter and Majeed Ahmad became Editor-in-Chief in August 2020.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] The website, *EDN Network*, caters to the needs of the working electrical engineer and covers new technologies and electronic component products at an engineering level.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] Columns discuss everything from managing engineers and engineering projects to technical issues faced in the design of electronic components, systems and developing technologies.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] The "Design Ideas" section features several user-submitted designs that are innovative or novel solutions to constrained design problems.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] Every issue features a column called "Prying Eyes" which disassembles a popular or intriguing consumer product and investigates the technologies that enable it.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] In May 2006, *EDN* won three awards from the *American Society of Business Publication Editors*.
[src:ee-times/edn-magazine] The Best Regular Department of the Year award went to "Prying Eyes".
[src:ee-times/ee-times] In July 2013, the digital edition migrated to UBM TechWeb's DeusM community platform.
[src:ee-times/ee-times] On June 3, 2016, UBM announced that *EE Times*, along with the rest of its electronics media portfolio (EDN, Embedded.com, TechOnline, and Datasheets.com), was being sold to AspenCore Media, a company owned by Arrow Electronics, for $23.5 million.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The earliest electronic design automation is attributed to IBM with the documentation of its 700 series computers in the 1950s.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] IBM has developed one of the earliest computer-aided design (CAD) systems, known as Automated Logic Diagram (ALD), which was originally executed on the IBM 704 and 705 mainframe computers.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The design process started with engineers manually drafting logic schematics, which were later transcribed onto standardized templates and converted into punch cards for digital processing.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Although focused on mechanical geometry, General Motors’ DAC-1, built jointly with IBM, was among the earliest interactive, graphics-driven CAD systems and proved the practicality of screen-based editing for complex engineering data, an idea adopted by IC layout tools.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Prior to the development of EDA, integrated circuits were designed by hand and manually laid out.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Some advanced shops used geometric software to generate tapes for a Gerber photoplotter, responsible for generating a monochromatic exposure image, but even those copied digital recordings of mechanically drawn components.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The process was fundamentally graphic, with the translation from electronics to graphics done manually; the best-known company from this era was Calma, whose GDSII format is still in use today.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] In the early 1970s, developers started to automate circuit design in addition to drafting and the first placement and routing tools were developed.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Because of the Cold War, developments often occurred in near parallel.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] In the Western world, the proceedings of the IEEE and the Design Automation Conference catalogued the large majority of the developments of the time, and by 1973 a large bibliography was needed to keep track of developments in the field.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] In the Soviet Union, progress was largely described in a series of books, starting in 1975.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Calma’s Graphic Design System (GDS, 1971) and its 32-bit successor GDSII (1978) let engineers digitise and edit full-chip layouts on minicomputers; the accompanying GDSII Stream file became the de-facto mask exchange standard and is still recognised in modern design flows.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The next era began following the publication of "Introduction to VLSI Systems" by Carver Mead and Lynn Conway in 1980, and is considered the standard textbook for chip design.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The result was an increase in the complexity of the chips that could be designed, with improved access to design verification tools that used logic simulation.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The chips were easier to lay out and more likely to function correctly, since their designs could be simulated more thoroughly prior to construction.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Although the languages and tools have evolved, this general approach of specifying the desired behavior in a textual programming language and letting the tools derive the detailed physical design remains the basis of digital IC design today.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The earliest EDA tools were produced academically.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] One of the most famous was the "Berkeley VLSI Tools Tarball", a set of UNIX utilities used to design early VLSI systems.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Widely used were the Espresso heuristic logic minimizer, responsible for circuit complexity reductions and Magic, a computer-aided design platform.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Another crucial development was the formation of MOSIS, a consortium of universities and fabricators that developed an inexpensive way to train student chip designers by producing real integrated circuits.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The basic concept was to use reliable, low-cost, relatively low-technology IC processes and pack a large number of projects per wafer, with several copies of chips from each project remaining preserved.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Cooperating fabricators either donated the processed wafers or sold them at cost, as they saw the program as helpful to their own long-term growth.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] 1981 marked the beginning of EDA as an industry.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] For many years, the larger electronic companies, such as Hewlett-Packard, Tektronix and Intel, had pursued EDA internally, with managers and developers beginning to spin out of these companies to concentrate on EDA as a business.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Daisy Systems, Mentor Graphics and Valid Logic Systems were all founded around this time and collectively referred to as DMV.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Department of Defense additionally began funding of VHDL as a hardware description language.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Within a few years, there were many companies specializing in EDA, each with a slightly different emphasis.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The first trade show for EDA was held at the Design Automation Conference in 1984, and in 1986, Verilog, another popular high-level design language, was first introduced as a hardware description language by Gateway Design Automation.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Simulators quickly followed these introductions, permitting direct simulation of chip designs and executable specifications.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Within several years, back-ends were developed to perform logic synthesis.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Current digital flows are extremely modular, with front ends producing standardized design descriptions that compile into invocations of units similar to cells without regard to their individual technology.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Cells implement logic or other electronic functions via the utilisation of a particular integrated circuit technology.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Fabricators generally provide libraries of components for their production processes, with simulation models that fit standard simulation tools.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Most analog circuits are still designed in a manual fashion, requiring specialist knowledge that is unique to analog design (such as matching concepts).
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Hence, analog EDA tools are far less modular, since many more functions are required, they interact more strongly and the components are, in general, less ideal.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] EDA for electronics has rapidly increased in importance with the continuous scaling of semiconductor technology.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Some users are foundry operators, who operate the semiconductor fabrication facilities ("fabs") and additional individuals responsible for utilising the technology design-service companies who use EDA software to evaluate an incoming design for manufacturing readiness.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] EDA tools are also used for programming design functionality into FPGAs or field-programmable gate arrays, customisable integrated circuit designs.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Synopsys announced a planned acquisition of Ansys in 2024, but Ansys remains an independent, publicly traded company until the deal closes (expected H1 2025).
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Many EDA companies acquire small companies with software or other technology that can be adapted to their core business.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] This is happening due to a trend to place entire electronic systems on a single chip.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Machine-learning methods are now applied at every major stage of the integrated-circuit design flow, from high-level synthesis through sign-off.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Machine-learning shortens turnaround times and improves power, performance and area (PPA).
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] EDA vendors have since integrated similar optimization engines into production toolchains.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] The OpenROAD Project (Foundations and Realisation of Open, Accessible Design), launched under DARPA’s IDEA program, released a no-human-in-the-loop RTL-to-GDS flow that has successfully taped-out designs.
[src:ee-times/electronic-design-automation] Conferences such as ORConf and the annual FOSSi Foundation roadmap sessions now dedicate substantial tracks to open-source EDA progress.
